caption: Table 1: Quantitative results of the proposed method and baselines. Our method outperforms the baselines across all datasets, as indicated by accuracy (%) ±plus-or-minus\pm± standard error. The highest values are highlighted in red, and the second-highest values are highlighted in blue. All results are reported over 500 fixed evaluation problems, expect GSM results for GPT-3.5 which are reported over 1000 fixed evaluation problems (to construct nonoverlapping confidence bars).
description: Table 1 presents a quantitative comparison of the proposed multi-agent finetuning method against several baseline methods across three distinct language reasoning tasks: Arithmetic, Grade School Math (GSM), and MATH.  The table shows the accuracy (percentage correct) and standard error for each method and dataset. The highest accuracy for each task is highlighted in red, and the second-highest is in blue.  The results demonstrate that the proposed method consistently achieves higher accuracy than the baselines across all three tasks, highlighting its effectiveness. Note that the number of evaluation problems differs slightly between datasets (500 for Arithmetic and MATH, 1000 for GSM in the GPT-3.5 model) to ensure statistically valid confidence intervals.

caption: Table 2: Ablation results. We examine each component of the proposed method and found that summarization, the combination of critic and generation agents, multiagent finetuning, and multiagent debate all contribute to performance improvement. The accuracy (%) ±plus-or-minus\pm± standard error is reported.
description: This table presents the results of ablation studies conducted on the proposed multiagent finetuning method.  The goal was to determine the contribution of each individual component of the method to the overall performance improvement. The components analyzed include summarization of agent responses, the use of critic agents in conjunction with generation agents, the multiagent finetuning process itself, and the use of multiagent debate. For each configuration, the table reports the accuracy (percentage) and the standard error, indicating the impact of removing each component on the model's accuracy.

caption: Table 3: Cooperative Finetuning. Our method supports fine-tuning in cooperative settings, where agents work together (e.g., 3 agents, 2 rounds).
description: This table presents the results of a cooperative finetuning experiment, showing how the proposed multiagent finetuning method performs when agents collaborate to generate responses instead of competing.  It demonstrates the effectiveness of the method across three different tasks (Arithmetic, GSM, MATH), using different language models (LLMs).  The table compares the performance of the base model, a multiagent finetuning method where agents cooperate, against other methods that were finetuned in competitive settings or where a single agent was finetuned. The cooperative setting involves having three agents work together for two rounds to generate responses.

caption: Table 5: Unique ID vs Multiagent Finetuning. We introduce an additional comparison to multiagent finetuning where we feed a unique ID token to each agent, corresponding to a generation or critic agent. We find that this is not comparable to improvements on multiagent finetuning.
description: This table compares the performance of two methods for improving language models: multiagent finetuning and using unique IDs. In multiagent finetuning, multiple language models work together, each specializing in a different aspect of the task.  In the unique ID method, each model is given a unique identifier. The table shows that multiagent finetuning significantly outperforms the unique ID method on the MATH dataset. The results indicate that the collaborative approach of multiagent finetuning is more effective than simply providing unique IDs to individual models.

description: This table presents an additional evaluation of the multiagent finetuning method on more challenging mathematical problems.  The MATH dataset was used, with problems sampled from all five difficulty levels, making it more difficult than previous evaluations.  The results demonstrate that the multiagent finetuning approach continues to outperform baseline methods even on these more complex tasks, highlighting the robustness and broad applicability of the technique.

The results indicate the effectiveness of the proposed multiagent finetuning method compared to various baseline approaches.
